node.text:
What does this image look like to you?

🐘  It may take some imagination to understand why this is known as the Elephant’s Trunk Nebula. Some might instead see a fleeing ghost or even a long-tailed betta fish.

🐘  This glowing stellar nursery is being sculpted by winds and radiation from a massive star located out of the field of view at left. This infrared image, courtesy of the Spitzer Space Telescope, gives a preview of what the James Webb Space Telescope will provide.

🐘  Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech/W. Reach (SSC/Caltech)

🐘  #WorldElephantDay #Nebula #NASAWebb

node.text:
From vision ➡️ to reality

Swipe right to compare an early concept of the James Webb Space Telescope (then named the Next Generation Space Telescope) with the Webb telescope as it is today.

Before the Hubble Space Telescope was even launched, scientists and engineers were already asking the question — what’s next?

You'll notice that early designs of Webb don’t look too different from the completed version of the telescope now, incorporating a segmented mirror, an “open” design, and a large sunshield.

Credit: [1] NASA; [2] NASA/Chris Gunn

node.text:
Don’t let the serene, calming nature of NGC 891 fool you. Within its churning layers of gas and dust—and outflows bursting from the galaxy’s central plane—lie intense pockets of star formation. ✨

That’s why the James Webb Space Telescope researchers are planning to use the telescope’s unmatched sensitivity to resolve how the composition of that gas and dust impacts the star formation rate.

This image highlights the spiral galaxy’s northern half, with the galaxy’s central bulge located just outside of view at bottom left.

#NASAWebb #Hubble #UnfoldtheUniverse #galaxies

Credit: ESA/Hubble & NASA; Nick Rose.

node.text:
🌟 WEBB INTERN SPOTLIGHT: Meet Alyson Wirtz 🌟

“Hi, I’m Alyson and I’m a student at @uhmanoanews studying astronomy. I am also an intern at NASA working on a research project for the James Webb Space Telescope. The project that I am working on is focused on early galaxies that formed after the Big Bang occurred.

Being accepted to be a part of this team is something I have dreamed about for my whole life and the reality of it is so much better than I could have ever imagined. What I feel helped me get this internship position was being really honest with the people who interviewed me by telling them how passionate I was about space exploration. I believe they could really tell how much it meant to me and how determined I was to be successful.

When I finally got accepted and started to work, I’ve made every attempt to reach out and make connections along the way. I believe networking is very important and in doing so you get to make many more great memories. So far, my favorite memory has been seeing the Webb telescope in person. This has really given me a complete overall experience since we have been virtual this whole time. I encourage all of you to follow your passions and to never give up on your dreams because anything is possible. In my free time I love being in nature, traveling, and stargazing.”

node.text:
🌟 WEBB INTERN SPOTLIGHT: Meet Lindsey Jacobson 🌟

“My name is Lindsey Jacobson, and I'm a rising senior at @ncstate studying Aerospace Engineering with a minor in Industrial Engineering. Last summer, I reviewed the risk management process for Webb to determine and document why each technical risk was accepted. I also suggested further actions that could be taken to provide greater confidence in mission success. This summer, I am creating a preliminary risk assessment for future space telescope concepts based on lessons learned from the design and development of Webb.
 
I wanted to work for NASA since I was a freshman in high school. I originally wanted to be an Astrophysicist after being inspired by the @NASAHubble images we studied in environmental science. Later, I became interested in Aerospace Engineering when I toured @nasakennedy and learned how the concept of the space shuttle was developed. It was at that point that I really saw the beauty in engineering design. I am really grateful that I’ve been able to work with Webb because it has allowed me to combine my passion for engineering design with my love of astrophysics.
 
For anyone who is interested in pursuing a NASA internship, my best advice would be to just go for it. NASA has so many opportunities to get involved with projects across all disciplines. Find the opportunities that you're most interested in, apply early, and reach out to internship mentors and coordinators if you can. Don't stop putting yourself out there once you get the internship either. Some of the most meaningful conversations I've had at NASA have stemmed from sending cold emails to engineers working on projects that I'm interested in. The workplace culture at NASA is so supportive and welcoming. The internship is really what you make of it!”

“Hello, I’m Korey Carter. I study mechanical engineering at @universityofdc. This summer, I’m working as a systems engineering intern for Webb focusing on risk analysis. node.text:
🌟 WEBB INTERN SPOTLIGHT: Meet Mikayla Huffman 🌟

“Hi everyone! My name is Mikayla Huffman, and I am a rising senior at @william_and_mary in Virginia. I’m on the honors track for physics with minors in geology and math. I own a ball python named Beaker (pictured) and a bearded dragon named Stu. I play in two Dungeons & Dragons campaigns and am the dungeon master for a third. I also do a lot of cosplay in my free time. (Included here is my suit of Mandalorian armor that I built from scratch!) This summer, I’m working on Jupiter family comet spectroscopy — if we can figure out what comets are made of, we can infer what the early solar system was like.

I’ve always known NASA was going to be a part of my life. I remember being a little kid staying up late to watch a meteor shower with my parents. Laying there suspended over the great sea of the sky, being held to the Earth by the tenuous strings of gravity makes you feel small. But space also makes us feel big. Because it reminds us that when we work together for a common goal, we can accomplish great things. When I look up at the moon and know that humans have walked there, it brings me hope because we did it together as a country, not just as individuals.
 
NASA started with a blank canvas and painted a masterpiece that has yet to be finished. We can all add to it. And even if I can’t explore the universe on my own, I can still pave the way for others who will. The fact that one of NASA’s core values is Diversity & Inclusion means a lot to me as a queer woman. Marian Edelman says, “You can’t be what you can’t see.” Having visible scientists that don’t look like the ‘stereotypical scientist’ is essential to improving diversity in STEM. This opportunity has shown me what working at NASA is like, and I know that I have found my place here.”

node.text:
🌟 WEBB INTERN SPOTLIGHT: Meet Joanna Pullen 🌟 

"My name is Joanna and I am a NASA Education Intern on the Webb team. Last year I graduated with a Masters in Education from @coloradostateuniversity and began my first year as a Science Educator. I also have my degree in Meteorology from @unc_colorado.

I applied to NASA internships over many years, never being accepted, but due to my determination to be a part of NASA’s amazing work, I remained motivated and was chosen as an intern this summer in my most recent application. I like to share this when talking about my journey, because it is not always a straightforward path into NASA. I want people to know that if you do not get chosen, do not give up – look at it as an opportunity for growth.

My favorite thing about the projects I am working on is that they give me new perspectives into the field of education, which ultimately will make me a stronger educator. This experience has only further inspired me to remain in the field of STEM education. My ultimate career goal is to work as a formal or informal education and outreach specialist at NASA. Outside of work my hobbies include traveling, crafting, snowboarding, hiking, camping, and playing with my dog, Toby, who doubles as my work from home buddy."
